I spent a lot of time on the Gulf Coast, and have eaten more than one bowl of gumbo. "Kickin' Kajun" strikes me as a foreigner's impression of what Cajun cuisine could taste like. You will probably prefer this place if you do not have preconceptions of what your meal should be. The seasoning is just about right - but something feels a little off. Not bad, just... not what you might remember.  Parking is the usual mess for that area. There is a lot nearby, but there are fewer spaces than there are seats in the surrounding restaurants. I parked down the street at the DonQ, but you could try the WallMart or Ross lots if you plan on shopping there later. Once you arrive, it is noisy inside. You may have to shout to be heard, but there is a festive atmosphere. It can be crowded, with elbows and knees rubbing. This is a place to bring friends and celebrate.  With the aforementioned caveats about the food... Southern sweet-tea it ain't. The fried baskets were pretty good, but there were no po'boy sandwiches on the menu, which is confounding to this po'boy. All they need to add is a hoagie roll toasted with garlic butter! Their boiled seafood was somewhat unexpected. These are not Gulf Coast spiny or slipper lobsters, nor are they green or blue crabs. They have substituted Pacific options, which is okay. I found it amusing that they provided gloves to everyone, but no crab-mallets or crab-crackers to crush limbs of the arthropod of your choosing. You can cut open your sea-legs with a pair of sturdy scissors. It works, but again, it isn't what I grew up with. Not bad - just different. Good to eat communally - break some stuff apart with friends.  Flavorwise, I ordered "spicy" hot, but found it muted. The flavor was interesting, and just about right for Cajun. Good garlic, but it didn't soak into my crawdads very thoroughly. You're not eating the crunchy bits outside with the flavoring, so I recommend dunking your meat back into the soup in the boil-bag for a soak while you continue peeling your crustaceans.  Not quite Louisiana, but this place seemed very popular with Japanese tourists.
